I wrote my first program at 13 years old!

Wait - Your mind is not blown??  

How about -  I wrote my first program at 13 years old in a Walmrt-like-store!

Still??

OK, here it it - my first program...

```
10 PRINT "BOOGER"
20 goto 10

```
I said I was 13...  (some code modified to be SFW) 

It was on a Commodore [VIC-20](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodore_VIC-20) and it was the summer of 1980...

![data:image/jpeg;base64,](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

I had wanted a [TRS-80](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TRS-80) for years but I didn't know what I would've done with it...  and they wouldn't let me play with it at Radio Shack...

![data:image/jpeg;base64,](data:image/jpeg;base64,) (Yes, that is a [cassette player](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodore_Datasette) - and that is how we saved data back then...)

That program is why I got into writing code!  not line 10, but the fact that I made a computer do something...  This meant the possibilities were endless!!!  I could endlessly repeat my name, or that someone sucked, or I could write a program to dominate the world - again, I was 13...

I was also lucky enough to have a friend whose Dad taught computer programing at a high school accross town and he would [bring one home](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodore_PET) some weekends: 
![https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Pet4016.png/220px-Pet4016.png](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Pet4016.png/220px-Pet4016.png)

For a couple of years I learned programing at the store and from my friend's Dad.  Finally, In high school, I learned in an organized way and things got so much more fun.  I even wrote my first (and only) game in high school, it was no "unar lander" game but I enjoyed it - wrestling via basc: "what move would you like to do?" a random number generator depending on difficulty of move determined if it worked or not "that worked - two point"/"he reversesd the move.  One point for your opponent" .  It didn't really go anywhere...

In university, I had a pretty solid B+ average in my programming classes but that still put me in the bottom third of the class - realizing that I was up against some pretty smart people, I put that on hold to figure out what I wanted to do...

I still did some programming/hacking during that time:  Setting up co-workers computers to great them like HAL 9000, setting their screen savers to read "Critical Data Compromised!!  Do not touch keyboard".  I even created a website a autostart CD for my brother to fundraise with after he made the olympic team in 1998.

In 2013, after many failed/successful career changes (hopitality, oil industry, TV/film industry, industrial mechanics, food manufacturing - and various levels of managment within each one) I decided to go back to school for computer science - this time for Computer Information Systems and cloud Technology.  A double major...

That wasn't quite challenging enough so when a cross country move offered another opportunity to redefine my career - I took it!  

and that how I got here... now...  and it was a fun journey - let me know if you want any of the stories...

So??
